CCP1 - First 2 items and non-DEEPEst DEEP

1. Summary

First 2 items (putting them into 4 groups) correlates highly with a similar non-DEEPEst measure that uses all 8 items. It is correlated at about r = .6 with DEEPEst delta and r = .15 with DEEPEst beta.

First 2 items significantly predicts search (whether measured as fixations or time spent searching). These effects are at least as strong as when using DEEPEst estimates.

First 2 items dont significantly predict accuracy in CCP1 (but neither do the DEEPEst analyses with all 8 items). Including all 8 items and doing non-DEEPEst analyses significantly predicts accuracy whereas DEEPEst DEEP does not.

2.2 First 2 DEEP items

Coded them into 4 groups; 0 = smaller sooner for both, 1 = SS 1st item, LL 2nd item, 2 = LL 1st item, SS 2nd item, 3 = LL for both.

And here are stats broken down by 1st item responses.

Of those who chose LL for first item and therefore saw this item ($248 today or $250 in 1 month), 91% chose SS.

This doesnt seem ideal. Maybe the priors entered in DEEP are off, but shouldnt the item generate something where roughly 50% choose each option?

Of those who chose SS for first item and therefore saw this item ($96 today or $300 in 2 weeks), 56% chose SS.

6. Inferential tests

It does at least as well as DEEPEst.

1st model is with 2 items of DEEP. 2nd model is with DEEPEst stochastic 5000 iterations
